<DOC><DOCNO> AP900222-0174 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-90 2114EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-IvoryCoast     02-22 0289</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Ivory Coast,0296</SECOND><HEAD>Soldiers Break Up Anti-Government Protests With Tear Gas, Clubs</HEAD><BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soldiers used tear gas and clubs todisperse hundreds of student deomonstrators Thursday in what hasbecome the largest outbreak of anti-government protest in years.   The government and the state-run news media have been silentabout the protests, which began Monday when students angered bycuts in water and power service demanded democracy and theresignation of President Felix Houphouet-Boigny.   At one point, Thursday's protesters assembled outside the statetelevision offices in suburban Cocody, shouting: ``Tell the truth!Tell the truth!'' They fled when soldiers and police attacked themwith truncheons.   Students said they tried to march on the presidential offices,but police and soldiers blocked them less than a mile from theuniversity.   Earlier in the day, police attacked more than 300 students asthey protested peacefully at the state university campus in Cocody,singing ``Greetings, Land of Hope,'' the national anthem.   A local resident said police and soldiers also fired tear gas atstudents who fled and tried to continue the demonstration.   Armed police in riot helmets sealed off the campus, but liftedthe blockade later the campus appeared calm.   Students said many had been injured since Monday. Police beatstudents who set two cars ablaze Monday night, and on Tuesdayofficers charged students who smashed the windows of two buses.   This pro-Western nation in West Africa, one of the continent'srichest, is struggling with a recession that has broughtunemployment, salary cuts and declining living standards.   Houphouet-Boigny, officially 84 years old but believed to be inhis 90s, has ruled Ivory Coast as a one-party state sinceindependence from France in 1960.</TEXT></DOC>